### GAUSSIAN BLUR CLASS

Gaussian blur is one of the most common techniques used to smooth an image and reduce noise.

Gaussian Blur recalculates the value of each pixel based on the weighted average of its neighboring pixels. These weights are determined according to the "Gaussian Distribution" (bell curve).

- **kernelSize**: This is the size of the area (matrix) where blurring will occur (3x3, 5x5). The larger it is, the more the image is blurred.
- **sigmaX**: This is the standard deviation of the Gaussian kernel. It determines the amount of "spread" of the blur. If 0 is given, it is automatically calculated according to the kernel size.
- **borderType**: Determines how the pixels at the edges of the image are processed (because edge pixels do not have a complete list of neighbors).
- BORDER_CONSTANT: Add black/constant color to the edges.
- BORDER_REPLICATE: Mirrors/extends edge pixels outwards. - BORDER_DEFAULT: A slightly smarter and improved version of the BORDER_REFLECT method. It uses the edge of the image like a mirror but does not repeat the outermost pixel.

### ROTATE CLASS:

For now, we are only adding the Interpolation parameter to the **Rotate** operation.

This parameter directly affects image quality by determining how pixels are recalculated when the image is rotated.

Here are the interpolation options we will use and their meanings:

- **Bicubic (Highest Quality):** Takes into account the surrounding 16 pixels. Provides the smoothest and highest quality result, but requires more processing power.
- **Bilinear (Medium Quality):** Takes into account the surrounding 4 pixels. It is a balance between speed and quality.
- **Nearest Neighbor (Fastest):** Looks at the closest single pixel. It is fast, but may cause aliasing at the edges after rotation.

